[
    {
        "content": "<p>Hello everyone, i'm trying to concatenate 2 Cstr, i tried concat and join but they only work on &amp;str. Are there any ways to do this?</p>",
        "id": 434313919,
        "sender_full_name": "Ranim Damak",
        "timestamp": 1713515495
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Are these compile-time constants that you're concatenating at compile-time?</p>",
        "id": 434314154,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1713515582
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Or is this a runtime operation?</p>",
        "id": 434314211,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1713515601
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>it's in compile-time.</p>",
        "id": 434314823,
        "sender_full_name": "Ranim Damak",
        "timestamp": 1713515837
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In a const fn where they are parameters, or a macro? Perhaps you could share an example?</p>",
        "id": 434315160,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1713515971
    },
    {
        "content": "<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">fn</span> <span class=\"nf\">concat_cstr</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;'</span><span class=\"na\">a</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span>: <span class=\"kp\">&amp;</span><span class=\"o\">'</span><span class=\"na\">a</span> <span class=\"nc\">CStr</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span>: <span class=\"kp\">&amp;</span><span class=\"o\">'</span><span class=\"na\">a</span> <span class=\"nc\">CStr</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span>-&gt; <span class=\"kp\">&amp;</span><span class=\"o\">'</span><span class=\"na\">a</span> <span class=\"nc\">CStr</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a_bytes</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">as_bytes</span><span class=\"p\">();</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b_bytes</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">as_bytes</span><span class=\"p\">();</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">mut</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">concat_bytes</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nb\">Vec</span>::<span class=\"n\">try_with_capacity</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a_bytes</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">len</span><span class=\"p\">()</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b_bytes</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">len</span><span class=\"p\">()</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"p\">);</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">concat_bytes</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">expect</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"s\">\"REASON\"</span><span class=\"p\">).</span><span class=\"n\">try_extend_from_slice</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a_bytes</span><span class=\"p\">).</span><span class=\"n\">unwrap</span><span class=\"p\">();</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"c1\">//concat_bytes.expect(\"REASON\").try_push(0);</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">concat_bytes</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">expect</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"s\">\"REASON\"</span><span class=\"p\">).</span><span class=\"n\">try_extend_from_slice</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">b_bytes</span><span class=\"p\">).</span><span class=\"n\">unwrap</span><span class=\"p\">()</span><span class=\"o\">?</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">CStr</span>::<span class=\"n\">from_bytes_with_nul</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"o\">&amp;</span><span class=\"n\">concat_bytes</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">).</span><span class=\"n\">unwrap</span><span class=\"p\">()</span>\n\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Here's my exemple</p>",
        "id": 434317111,
        "sender_full_name": "Ranim Damak",
        "timestamp": 1713516742
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's not possible to implement a function with that signature, because it requires that the concatenated string already exists somewhere in memory. You'll need a different return type.</p>",
        "id": 434317512,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1713516887
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If it was at runtime, the correct return type would be <code>CString</code>, but since you said you want this to happen at compile-time I need a bit more info.</p>",
        "id": 434317613,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1713516928
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Could you show the code that is using <code>concat_cstr</code> so I can better understand how it is used?</p>",
        "id": 434317682,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1713516958
    },
    {
        "content": "<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"k\">fn</span> <span class=\"nf\">serialize</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"o\">&amp;</span><span class=\"bp\">self</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span>-&gt; <span class=\"kp\">&amp;</span><span class=\"nc\">CStr</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">serialized_frame1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">CStr</span>::<span class=\"n\">from_bytes_with_nul</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"o\">&amp;</span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"bp\">self</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">length</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">self</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">mode</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">self</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">pid</span><span class=\"p\">]).</span><span class=\"n\">unwrap</span><span class=\"p\">();</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">serialized_frame2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">CStr</span>::<span class=\"n\">from_bytes_with_nul</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"o\">&amp;</span><span class=\"bp\">self</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">data</span><span class=\"p\">).</span><span class=\"n\">unwrap</span><span class=\"p\">();</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">serialized_frame</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">unsafe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">CStr</span>::<span class=\"n\">from_bytes_with_nul_unchecked</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Obd2Frame</span>::<span class=\"n\">concat_cstr</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">serialized_frame1</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"n\">serialized_frame2</span><span class=\"p\">).</span><span class=\"n\">as_ref</span><span class=\"p\">())</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">};</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">serialized_frame</span>\n\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 434318035,
        "sender_full_name": "Ranim Damak",
        "timestamp": 1713517087
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The signature of <code>serialize</code> is also an issue. The signature is essentially saying that it's returning a reference to some string data that already exists inside <code>self</code> somewhere.</p>",
        "id": 434318310,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1713517201
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Could you show the caller of <code>serialize</code>?</p>",
        "id": 434318569,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1713517268
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm still in the process of writing the modules so I still don't have function calls yet. Meanwhile I have questions if you don't mind:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p>Why can't I use function like push, with_capacity (Generates a compiler error <code>function or associated item not found in Vec&lt;_, _&gt;</code> and it indicates to use the try_push or try_with_capacity?</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>How do I use functions from the <code>alloc</code> crate i.e macros like <code>format!</code>?</p>\n</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 434333434,
        "sender_full_name": "Ranim Damak",
        "timestamp": 1713522554
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Does your branch have <a href=\"https://lore.kernel.org/rust-for-linux/20240328013603.206764-1-wedsonaf@gmail.com/\">Wedson's allocation APIs</a> patchset? It's in rust-next and should go upstream in the next kernel version.</p>",
        "id": 434334744,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1713523067
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Without that patchset, the methods you want are indeed the <code>try_*</code> methods. With the patchset, the answer is different. It provides methods called <code>push</code> and so on that take gfp flags as an argument.</p>",
        "id": 434334897,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1713523115
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>As for the <code>format!</code> macro, what you should use there is <code>CString::try_from_fmt</code> from <code>rust/kernel/str.rs</code>. The documentation for that method has some examples for how to use it.</p>",
        "id": 434335192,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1713523235
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But as a general note, anything in the alloc crate that does allocations without giving you the opportunity to handle allocation failures will not be usable in the kernel.</p>",
        "id": 434335805,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1713523490
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm actually using the rust branch, would changing to the rust-next branch provide these APIs?<br>\nAs for the <code>format!</code> macro, i am already using <code>CString::try_from_fmt</code>.</p>",
        "id": 434338963,
        "sender_full_name": "Ranim Damak",
        "timestamp": 1713524770
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>the rust branch is no longer used, see <a href=\"https://rust-for-linux.com/branches\">https://rust-for-linux.com/branches</a></p>",
        "id": 434339371,
        "sender_full_name": "Ariel Miculas",
        "timestamp": 1713524929
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The rust branch is very very old. It'll be hard to help you if you are on such an outdated branch.</p>",
        "id": 434339377,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1713524931
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I see. Thank you!</p>",
        "id": 434339796,
